@node Overview
@chapter Welcome to Net Machine Emulator

Net Machine Emulator, or NME, provides a general-purpose framework for
computer emulation or even hardware simulation. The end goal is to
create a library of modules, each being an element emulating a specific
machine component, like computer chip, bus, board, or anything else
needed to describe a ``machine'' at a higher level. In this context,
a machine is defined as a computational device, such as an actual
general-purpose computer like PC, desktop, workstation, or even a phone.
However, it can also be a special-purpose machine, such as a NIC, FPGA,
GPU, or even a hardware simulator in itself like a Verilog simulation.

In addition, it provides facilities for emulating standard external
components not part of the machine proper, such as displays and network
interfaces. As such, you can create fully working virtual machines
that work just like the physical hardware they are emulating.
These modules offer standard interfaces that allow you to
connect them together to create a whole machine emulation with minimum
effort and maximum efficiency.

NME is flexible enough to provide a provide a description at any level
of complexity. This is because it takes a reductionist approach rather
than the holistic approach of most other emulators. Those emulators are
usually designed for a specific machine or purpose such that they are
specialized to doing specific tasks required for those architectures.
Obviously, this can result in better performance at a higher level of
abstraction, but there is obviously a trade-off in the accuracy of
the description. As a result, they might miss some requirements needed
for more subtle operational features which could manifest as incorrect
or inaccurate operation under certain conditions.

While it might seem that these assembled machine emulations will
never be as fast as a single program designed from the beginning to
emulate a specific machine at a high level, the individual modules can
be specified at any level. So, in theory, a whole ``machine'' could
be described at a course-grained abstraction level, and then connected to
another machine assembled from fine-grained components. For instance,
if you're mainly interested in simulating a whole computer from a
component-based description, but have a peripheral ``machine'' that
might already be implemented by another emulation, it is possible
to connect them in a machine description with sufficient adapters.

The trade-off NME takes can be seen as the overhead of the interfaces
between components. These interfaces can be connected at compile-time
(components assembled via a static build into a complete program)
or at run-time (dynamic build with components implemented by
shared libraries loaded at run-time). Even if the component interfaces
might introduce some overhead when connected dynamically, the overhead
can be minimized by compiling the program statically with higher levels
of optimization applied. In addition, they allow a great deal of
reusability and flexibility for describing different machines with the
same components, and making it easier to assemble different configurations
more quickly to see how they work together. This should save a lot of
development and test time, resulting in quicker turnaround time for
prototyping new systems. Performance issues can be addressed later by,
e.g., faster hardware or LTO whole-program compilation.

@node Introduction
@chapter What is NME?

NME is a generic machine emulation system for emulating one or more
machines. Each of the machines is specified in a special, extensible
machine description language (MDL) called nmesh script. It includes an
interpreter for this language that is used to translate the
description into a working, dynamical system that emulates the
machine. The elements of the language are keywords that name
individual components of the machine. Each component is implemented
using dynamically loaded modules that are compiled directly into
native machine code. In this way, it is very similar to a virtual
machine and is what makes it so efficient compared to many other
systems which may interpret the individual component descriptions.

The machine description itself is interpreted, but it creates a
statically connected system comprised of multiple dynamic modules that
are themselves compiled. As each component keyword is translated, the
components they describe get instantiated. This means that the
component module is dynamically loaded into the main running
program. In addition, components are connected via the "at"
keyword. When they are connected, a communications path is established
between the components. The path is dependent upon the interfaces
presented by the components. This means that the components must have
compatible interfaces in order to be connected using "at". The
communications protocols are determined by the components as well, and
must obviously be compatible. In this way, the machine description
language is very close to how an actual technical specification might
be accomplished. This makes it a prime candidate for use in
prototyping systems as well as for distributing dynamic specifications
of production systems. It could also be a potential candidate for a
future board-level (or network-level) ESL system (like SystemC) that
actually compiles the MDL into an HDL such as Verilog or VHDL and from
there into actual hardware systems with associated software
toolchains. The possibilities are limitless!

A good way to think of NME is that it is to machines what SPICE is to
circuits. In SPICE, the components can be standard, primitive devices
like resistors, diodes, and transistors, described using physical
constraints. They can be connected to form complex electronic circuits
which may then be simulated. Models of new components can be created
in the SPICE language to provide novel circuit elements. In the same
way, the elements in NME can be standard "primitive" components like
ICs, memories, busses, or external devices like NICs and disk
drives. New types of components can be modelled by coding their
behaviour directly in C source code which, when compiled, exports the
required interfaces as dynamically loaded modules using the extremely
portable GNU libltdl. They are combined to form more complex systems
such as computers that may then be emulated.

@node Installation
@chapter Installation

NME is already available on some systems through their packaging
systems. First check if your host platform of choice has it available
as source to build or binaries to install from a ports or package manager,
respectively, as that might be easier.
This also has the advantage of addressing any peculiarities or
idiosyncracies that might arise on that platform. In that case, you should refer
to their documentation for how to install NME & associated packages on those systems.

If your system already has NME available through a ports or packages
management system, you can skip these steps, as they should be handled
automatically by them. One disadvantage is that they might not be
up-to-date with the latest distribution, so you should check if there is a
newer version available. In that case, you might want to build it
from scratch anyway to get the latest features and bug fixes. You
might also want to build directly from the github source repo, but
be aware that the tip could be broken at any point.

@menu
* Prerequisites:: Host package dependencies for building or using NME
* Building:: Building & installing NME on a host system
@end menu

@node Prerequisites
@section Prerequisites

Being a highly flexible, extensible emulation system, NME can take
advantage of many existing packages to provide certain services. As such, you
will want to install a number of these for smooth operation. If installing NME
from a ports or package management system, these dependencies should automatically
be handled for you. Likewise, you can probably find most, if not all, the
dependencies themselves in these packaging systems and install them directly from there.

@menu
* Required tools:: Tools needed to build from a source distribution
* Recommended libraries:: Recommended libraries providing host services
* Optional utilities:: Required if building from github repo
@end menu

@node Required tools
@subsection  Required tools needed to build a source distribution

If building from a source distribution of NME, you should first have
certain tools already installed on your host platform of choice.  The Required
tools should already be installed. On most major platforms of interest, these are
normally either available by default or through some sort of development meta-package.

@table @code

@item GCC or Clang/LLVM toolchain
NME has been successfully compiled using the two major non-VC toolchains

@item GNU Bison
For generating parser for nmesh input grammar, default YACC generally doesn't work

@item GNU Libtool
For building portable libraries

@item Make
Makefiles should be portable to GNU & BSD, at least, and possibly others

@item Perl
For included scripts like nme-sun-idprom & nme-sun-eeprom

@item pkgconf or pkg-config
For setting correct compiler & linker flags for package libraries

@end table

@node Recommended libraries
@subsection Recommended libraries that provide host services

It is highly suggested that you install the Recommended libraries, particularly
if you want a non-textual GUI. The Optional packages are for doing certain
tasks that you might need or want to do in some cases, like regenerating built
sources or automating tedious tasks. When building from source, the configure
step will inform you of any missing required dependencies, but not the
recommended or optional ones.

The @strong{libopenvpn} library is also provided
by the author and can be built with NME if included in the distribution.
It can also be downloaded on its own and either built & installed
before NME, or extracted into the libopenvpn subdirectory of the nme source root
to be built with it as a subproject.

@table @code

@item libopenvpn
Needed to build & run NME as well as for the openvpn networking host

@item GNU libltdl
Portable dynamic loader for using libtool. Built if not found on host system

@item Glib2
For glib threads; automatically included if GTK host enabled
      
@item GTK4 or GTK+3
To enable the gtk display host to emulate a monitor on a GUI

@item libvncserver
To enable the vnc display host to emulate monitor on a remote desktop

@item SDL3 or SDL2
To enable the sdl display host to emulate a monitor on a GUI and for sdl threads

@item libcpucycles
To use the optimal cycle counter found on the host platform

@end table

